INSERT INTO `facts` VALUES ('1','Along with setting the foundation for the nation, Washington also thought of the cabinet system, the inaugural address, and the title of \"Mr. President.\"','Washington was the only president to be elected by unanimous vote along with not being affiliated with a political party.'),('2','Adams wanted to emphasize a strong navy in the face of Europe and became known as the father of the American Navy.','Adams was the first president to live in the White House, be vice president, and have a political party.'),('3','By the pursuit of shipping and trade interests, Jefferson nearly doubled the territory of the United States and made temporary peace with France.','Jefferson was a polymath whose interests included agriculture, archeology (father of American scientific archeology), architecture (designed Monticello), astronomy, economics, geography, language (spoke more than 7 languages), law, and surveying.'),('4','Due to the War of 1812 and general opposition from the east, Madison supported a stronger national bank (which he had opposed earlier) and military.','Madison authored the Bill of Rights and is widely considered the Father of the Constitution.'),('5','Monroe improved the national state by buying Florida from Spain, performing a well recieved tour of the nation to ease bipartisan tension, and extend U.S. influence from the Atlantic to the Pacific.','Monroe was the last of the Founding Fathers to become president.  He also studied law under Thomas Jefferson.'),('6','Adams molded the U.S. foreign policy to successfully keep the nation independent from European politics.  Consequently, the nation was able to strengthen its foundation.','Adams was the first president to be the son of another president (John Adams).  He was also the first president to make a pragmatic stance against slavery by claiming that the nation would break into a civil war over it.'),('7','The popularity, stubborness, and military prowess of Jackson delayed a premature civil war when South Carolina wanted to secede.  With the threat of military might, he did not allow states to leave the union and saved the U.S. from an early demise.','When a man insulted the honor of the first lady, Jackson killed him in a duel.  Another man attempted the first presidential assassination on Jackson but he misfired twice and was beaten half to death in public by the president himself.'),('8','Van Buren built the modern Democratic Party during his time in office and from his influence before then.','Van Buren was very sociable.  He could mingle with upper class society as well as saloon environments.'),('9','Despite his unfortunately short time as president (only a month), the fate of Harrison posed a constitutional dilemma that would improve the presidential line of succession.','Harrison only served as president for a month before succumbing to pneumonia.  He was also the first president to be affiliated with the Whig political party and the oldest president to take office until Ronald Reagan.'),('10','Tyler was able to strengthen the Union by laying grounds to annex Texas.','Tyler was the first president to have his veto overridden by Congress.  He would veto a lot of the Whig bills to be unconstitutional, so he vetoed them at the chagrin of his party elected party.'),('11','Polk successfully annexed Texas from the victory of the Mexican-American War.  He also oversaw the opening of the U.S. Naval Academy, the Smithsonian Institution, and the issuance of the first postage stamps.','Often considered one of the greatest U.S. presidents, Polk successfully promoted, obtained support for, and achieved all of the major items on his presidential agenda.'),('12','During times of growing dissent between the North and the South, Taylor was able to maintain union by implementing the Compromise of 1850.','Taylor was reluctant to become president.  He had no interest in politics and an unclear platform.  However, he was still able to defeat his opponents through the admiration of the People and his peers.'),('13','Fillmore was able to open trade between the U.S. and Japan through naval expeditions.','Fillmore was the only president of the Whig part that did not die in office or get expelled from the party.'),('14','Pierce was elected as a compromise by the North with the South.  However, he polarized the groups further by signing the Kansas-Nebraska act and enforcing the Fugitive Slave Act.','Pierce lived a relatively tragic life.  His wife suffered from illness and depression for much of her life and their children all died young.  Their last son was killed in a gruesome train accident before the inauguration.'),('15','Buchanan was unable to broker peace between the North and the South, leading to the U.S. Civil War.','Although Buchanan aspired to be as esteemed as George Washington, he is often considered to be the worst presidents in U.S. history.  He is also the only president to remain a lifelong bachelor.'),('16','Lincoln led the nation through its bloodiest war and its greatest moral, constitutional, and political crisis.','The leader of a group of young ruffians decided to challenge Lincoln one day to a public wrestling match.  When Lincoln got the upper hand, the ruffians attempted to mob young Lincoln, but the future president was able to overpower them all.'),('17','Although he sought to maintain the Union, Johnson did not support laws that brought rights to slaves and consequently faced opposition.','Johnson was the first president to be impeached.  His main offense was violating the Tenure of Office Act that was passed by Congress.  Later, he became the first president to be acquitted.'),('18','Grant stabilized the nation during the critical Reconstruction period, prosecuted the Ku Klux Klan, protected African-American citizenship, and sought to remove vestiges of Confederate nationalism and slavery.','Grants birth name was \"Hiram Ulysses Grant,\" but the Congressman who sent a recommendation letter on behalf of Grant to West Point accidently referred to him as \"Ulysses S. Grant of Ohio.\"  This name became his adopted name.'),('19','Hayes was able to restore popular faith towards presidency, by enacted many modest changes that supported social justice and economic reform.','As a soldier in the Union army, Hayes garnered a reputation for bravery in combat and was wounded five times during his time with the army.'),('20','Despite his short time in office (less than a year), Garfield was able to energize American naval power, purge corruption in the Post Office, and bring a resurgence to presidential authority.','Garfields life was widely considered an American success story.  His life was a testament to the fact that even the poorest boy could become the President of the United States.'),('21','Arthur was abled to maintain state rights over federal enforcement regarding economics.  He also presided over the rebirth of the U.S. Navy.','Despite his lack of popularity in life and unspectacular term, Arthur is considered to be a successful president because he was able to avoid the substantial corruption that dominated business and politics at the time.'),('22','Cleveland relentlessly fought political corruption, patronage, and bossism.','Cleveland was the only president to serve two non-consecutive terms.'),('23','Harrison provided unprecedented economic legislation, facilitated the creation of National Forests through an amendment to the Land Revision Act of 1891, and substantially strengthened and modernized the Navy.','During his presidency, federal spending reached one billion dollars for the first time due to a surplus from tariffs.  Harrison is also the grandson of the 9th President, William Henry Harrison.'),('24','McKinley raised protective tariffs to promote American industry, led the nation to victory in the Spanish-American War, and maintained the gold standard by rejecting inflationary proposals.','McKinley currently holds the portrait on the U.S. $500 bill.'),('25','Roosevelt championed the Square Deal, promising the average citizen fairness, breaking of trusts, regulation of railroads, and pure food and drugs.  He also established many national parks, forests, and monuments to preserve natural resources.','Roosevelt was a sickly child with debiltating asthma.  However, by embracing a strenuous lifestyle, he overcame his physical malladies and enjoyed a vast range of interests.'),('26','Taft oversaw the passage of the Sixteenth Amendment and worked on civil service reform and improving the performance of the postal service.','Taft was close friends with Theodoore Roosevelt.  Roosevelt even supported his bid for the presidency.  However, once Taft was in office, Roosevelt became frustrated by the focus of the Taft presidency.'),('27','Despite efforts to keep the United States out of World War I, Wilson eventually led the nation through its side of the war.  He then sponsored the League of Nations, the precursor to the United Nations.','Wilson won a Nobel Peace Prize for sponsoring the League of Nations.  He was also an automobile enthusiast, which was part of why he advocated the funding of public highways.'),('28','Harding oversaw the Washington Naval Conference of 1921, which put significant limits on the major naval powers of the world for a decade.','Although he was very popular when his presidency ended, many scandals during his presidency arose posthumously and tarnished his public image.'),('29','After the scandals of Warren G. Harding, Coolidge restored public confidence in the White House.  He also reduced the size of government programs and federal power in general.','Coolidge was a very quiet man, but he had a fair sense of humor.  He was also the favorite 20th centruy U.S. president of future president Ronald Reagan because of his belief in a more limited federal government.'),('30','Hoover improved the efficiency of the government and the economy.  He also redistributed his salary after the beginning of the Great Depression a short 8 months after he took office.','Although Hoover was not directly responsible for the Great Depression, he is often blamed for it because he was in office at the time.  He gained an unfortunately unpopular image as a result.'),('31','Roosevelt led the nation through the great depression with his New Deal, which spearheaded national relief, recovery, and reform.  He also led the U.S. through the first half of World War II.','The enthusiasm, success, and impressive leadership of Roosevelt garnered an impressive public image that elected him to 4 terms as president, the most of any president.'),('32','Truman led the nation through the last stretch of World War II.  His presidency was also a turning point in U.S. foreign affairs by supporting an internationalist policy with European Allies.','Truman became popular as the head of the Truman Committee (formed in March 1941), which was an organization that exposed waste, fraud, and corruption in wartime contracts.'),('33','Eisenhower authorized the establishment of NASA and supported a more efficent military that required less spending.  He established considerable economic prosperity during his two terms.','Eisenhower loved golf.  He would play golf frequently and even establish a basic golf facility in Camp David.  He would also golf in the winter and ordered his golf balls to be black so that he could see them better in the snow.'),('34','Kennedy oversaw major domestic improvements regarding civil rights and reducing racial segregation.  He also established the Peace Corps and oversaw the building of the Berlin Wall.','The Kennedy administration was well known for having a charismatic leader.  Kennedy himself was an adamant supporter of civil rights.'),('35','Johnson designed the Great Society legislation, which upheld civil rights, public broadcasting, Medicare, Medicaid, aid of education, urban and rural development, public services, and his \"War on Poverty.\"','Johnson is one of 4 people to serve as the President, Vice President, and a member of both houses of Congress.'),('36','Nixon ended American involvement in the Vietnam War and was able to bring American prisoners of war home.  He established relations with China and initiated detente and the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty with the Soviet Union.','Nixon was the only president to have resigned from office.  He believed that impeachment was certain after the Watergate scandal, so he left before they would impeach him.'),('37','Ford signed the Helsinki Accords, marking a move toward detente in the Cold War.','Ford lived longer than any other U.S. president, reaching the age of 93 years and 165 days.  However, he was only president for 895 days, marking him as the president with the shortest term who did not die in office.'),('38','Carter pardoned all evaders of the Vietnam War drafts.  He also created the Department of Energy and the Department of Education.  He established a national energy policy that included conservation, price control, and new technology.','Most historians consider Carter to have made more influence after his presidency ended than during his presidency.  He set up the Carter Center to help in his advance of human rights and is a key figure in the Habitat for Humanity project.'),('39','Reagan was able to reduce inflation from 12.5% to 4.4% as well as increase average annual growth of real GDP by 3.44%.','Before becoming president, Reagan was an actor.  He began to tangle with politics when he was ordered to active duty with the U.S. Army.'),('40','Bush oversaw military operations in Panama and the Persian Gulf.','Before becoming president, Bush served as the Director of Central Intelligence under President Gerald Ford.'),('41','Clinton presided over the longest period of peacetime economic expansion in American history and signed into law the North American Free Trade Agreement.','Clinton created the William J. Clinton Foundation to address international issues, such as AIDS and global warming.'),('42','Bush signed into law broad tax cuts, the Patriot Act, the No Child Left Behind Act, Medicare prescription drug benegits for seniors, and funding for the AIDS relief program known as PEPFAR.','Bush is the second of only two presidents (the other being John Quincy Adams) to be the son of a former president.'),('43','Obama signed into law economic stimulus legislation such as the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 and the Tax Relief, Unemployment Insurance Reauthorization, and Job Creation Act of 2010.  He also ended U.S. involvement in the Iraq War.','Obama has a reputation for being very sociable.  He has often been seen (maybe more than any other president) enjoying non-political activities, such as playing basketball or watching a soccer game.');
